			<ns0:name>mseaborn@chromium.org</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/mseaborn@chromium.org/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">The omission of the long mode (LM) bit from x86-64 looks like a straightforward mistake which happened because the original x86-64 validator did not require the LM bit to be set.  (Checking for LM on an x86-64 machine is somewhat superfluous.)

Fixed feature mode was only intended to support x86-64 AFAIK, which is why x87 is disabled, so really tests/fixedfeaturecpu should be disabled for x86-32.

Brad Chen was the implementor/owner of this feature.</ns0:content><ns0:updated>2013-04-08T21:26:10.000Z</ns0:updated><ns0:published>2013-04-08T21:26:10.000Z</ns0:published><ns2:updates>
			<ns2:label>-Type-Enhancement</ns2:label><ns2:label>Type-Defect</ns2:label><ns2:status>Available</ns2:status><ns2:summary>Fixed CPU features are abnormal: "long mode" (LM) bit not set on x86-64</ns2:summary><ns2:ccUpdate>bradc...@google.com</ns2:ccUpdate></ns2:updates><ns0:title>Comment 2 by mseaborn@chromium.org</ns0:title><ns0:link href="http://code.google.com/p/nativeclient/issues/detail?id=3368#c2" rel="alternate" type="text/html" /><ns0:link href="https://code.google.com/feeds/issues/p/nativeclient/issues/3368/comments/full/2" rel="self" type="application/atom+xml" /></ns0:entry>